09241nam a22010455i 9780824860196DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248601967 a10.1515/97808248601962doi  a(DE-B1597)483950  a(OCoLC)794925333  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aNAT0100002bisacsh04a639.9/7792822200aConservation of Pacific Sea Turtles /ced. by Peter H. Dutton, Mahfuzuddin Ahmed, Dale Squires. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (544 p.) :b89 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction to the Conservation of Pacific Sea Turtles -- tPart One. Introduction -- tChapter 2. What Can Be Done to Restore Pacific Turtle Populations? -- tChapter 3. A Holistic Strategy for Pacific Sea Turtle Conservation -- tChapter 4. Can We Improve Our Conservation Bang for the Buck? -- tPart Two. Nesting Beaches -- tChapter 5. Nest Relocation -- tChapter 6. Tragedy of the Malaysian Leatherback Population -- tChapter 7. Conservation Project on Yakushima Island -- tChapter 8. Importance of Networks for Conservation of the Pacific Leatherback Turtle -- tChapter 9. Reconciling Dual Goals of Leatherback Conservation and Indigenous People’s Welfare -- tChapter 10. Projeto TAMAR-ICMBio -- tChapter 11. Direct Incentive Approaches for Leatherback Turtle Conservation -- tPart Three. Fisheries-Related Conservation -- tChapter 12. Fisheries Impacts on Sea Turtles in the Pacific Ocean -- tChapter 13. Managing Marine Turtles and Pelagic Fisheries on the High Seas -- tChapter 14. Which Commercial Swordfish Fishing Gear Is Best for Balancing Protected Species Conservation and Fishing Opportunity? -- tChapter 15. Sea Turtle Conservation in Peru -- tChapter 16. Sea Turtle–Fisheries Interactions in Coastal Fisheries -- tChapter 17. Can Coastal Fisheries Bear the Cost of Sea Turtle Conservation? -- tChapter 18. Performance and Technology Standards in International Environmental Agreements -- tChapter 19. Policies to Reduce Stochastic Sea Turtle Bycatch -- tChapter 20. The Conservation of Sea Turtles under the Law of the Sea Convention, the UN Fish Stocks Agreement, and the WCPF Convention -- tChapter 21. Trade and the Environment -- tAppendix: Action Plan Developed by the Nesting Beach Working Group as Part of the Bellagio Sea Turtle Conservation Initiative Workshop Held in Terengganu, Malaysia (July 2007) -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross the Pacific, populations of some species of sea turtles face extinction unless recent dramatic declines are reversed. The continuing decline of leatherbacks and loggerheads in particular illustrates the limitations of the current gradual and unilateral approach to conservation. Recovery requires instead a holistic solution that addresses all sources of mortality throughout the entire life history and habitat use of these transnational populations.Historically conservation efforts have focused on nesting sites to protect eggs and breeding females; mortality from coastal and highseas fisheries was not addressed. In the past five years, these recovery efforts have widened to include rigorously curtailing fishing and technological fixes that lower rates of incidental sea turtle deaths during fishing. Although each of these approaches shows promise, it has become increasingly clear that they alone will not recover severely depleted populations.Recognizing the urgency of the problem, this book presents ideas and case studies by conservation biologists, economists, marine life policy experts, fishing industry and fisheries professionals, management specialists, and development assistance researchers. It provides a new synthesis and blueprint for action that shifts the paradigm from piecemeal and unilateral conservation to a more holistic and multilateral approach to the recovery of Pacific sea turtle populations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh1 aAhmed, Mahfuzuddin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhmed, Mahfuzuddin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlfaro-Shigueto, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarragán, Ana Rebeca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalzell, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDutton, Donna L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDutton, Peter H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDutton, Peter H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFahy, Christina C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarner, Jeanne A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGjertsen, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroves, Theodore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeberer, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHitipeuw, Creusa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogan, David F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHong, Meen Chee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIbrahim, Kamarruddin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInouye, Daniel K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJit, Joytishna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKam